# using join in pandas to merge two columns 

city_count = spill_data['Site Municipality'].value_counts()[:3]

cities_affected = spill_data[['Site Municipality','Receiving Media']].merge(
   right=city_count, 
   left_on='Site Municipality',
   right_index=True).value_counts()[:10]
cities_affected = cities_affected.reset_index(name='Spill Count')

In [30]:
# using join in pandas to merge two dataframes 

city_count = spill_data['Site Municipality'].value_counts()[:3]

# self join on unique city names
cities_affected = spill_data[['Site Municipality','Receiving Media']].merge(
   right=city_count, 
   left_on='Site Municipality',
   right_index=True)

# joining the contamination_of_resource and cities_affected dataframes on Site Municipality
affected_resources = contamination_of_resource[['Date Reported','Contaminant Name','Receiving Media','Site Municipality']].merge(
   right=city_count, 
   left_on='Site Municipality',
   right_index=True)
affected_resources = affected_resources.sort_values(by='Date Reported')
affected_resources.head(5)

# Filter data to initial year  
year = affected_resources['Date Reported'].dt.year.min()
data = affected_resources[affected_resources['Date Reported'].dt.year == year]

# Creating the  
fig = px.bar(affected_resources, y="count", x="Date Reported", color='Receiving Media',hover_data=['Contaminant Name','Site Municipality'],labels={
                     "count": "Spill Count",
                     "Date Reported": "Date Reported for spill",
                     "Receiving Media": "Resources Polluted"
                 },
                 title='Top 3 Polluted Resources due to fuel spill (2003-2022)')
